 "completion": {
  "kind": "analysis",
  "analysis_id": null,
  "narrative": "## The trajectory\nApple compounded revenue from $260.2B [1] to $391.0B [2] across six fiscal years \u2014 an +8.5% CAGR \u2014 but the journey was two distinct acts: an explosive FY2021 (+33.3% YoY) followed by three essentially flat years, including a -2.8% dip in FY2023.\n\n## Growth quality\nGrowth has gotten harder. The post-FY2021 plateau shows top-line YoY oscillating around zero while net income slipped from its FY2022 peak of $99.8B [3] to $93.7B [4] \u2014 earnings are no longer outpacing revenue.\n\n## Margins\nNet margin expanded sharply in FY2021 to 25.9% [5], held near that level for two years, then eased to 24.0% [6] in FY2024 \u2014 still far above the pre-FY2021 ~21% base.\n\n## Cash & balance sheet\nCash generation remains the franchise: free cash flow of $108.8B [7] in FY2024 exceeds net income, and long-term debt has been worked down to $85.8B [8] from its FY2021 peak. Equity keeps shrinking by design (buybacks), so leverage ratios need that context.\n\n## Red flags\nNothing structural in these numbers \u2014 the flat top line since FY2022 is the watch item, not a defect.\n\n## What to watch next\nWhether FY2025 revenue re-accelerates beyond the +2.0% of FY2024, and whether net margin stabilizes above 24%.",
